National Trust spies on bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a Highland Scottish landscape, seeks to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
All findings are expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano pipistrelle bats, as well as Daubenton's bat and the long-eared brown bat in the gardens at Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track bat activity during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
The experts will analyse the sounds recorded to discover the frequency of bat calls and which species make them.
A habitat report and map will then be produced to provide a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS Conservation Adviser, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be managed for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind,
Instead, owing to its nocturnal hunting habits, its hearing is more useful than its eyesight in achieving its prey.
They use sophisticated ecolocation techniques to locate ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, rescue operations.
The Trust has even opened the first and only reserve dedicated to bats in Scotland at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
Here at Threave we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still much that is unknown about bats, so the work we are doing here and elsewhere will help us to understand better what they need to develop."
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before maintenance work is carried out within the property, as a breeding colony could be unintentionally destroyed and up to 400 females and young could be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, or to destroy their colonies.
The Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, Elisabeth Ferrell, has encouraged the public to help.
He said: 'We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we do not know how their populations are evolving.'
