The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first salvos of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still a long way to go before the battle is over, a rupture between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, the US president, issued the first warning in early 2018 by imposing tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs on $200 billion (£150 billion) of goods, taxing half of the goods that come into the United States from China.
On all occasions, Beijing has retaliated in kind, recently imposing tariffs of 5 to 10 per cent on $60 billion worth of American products.
China has committed to matching the United States, and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will soon ease up.
To back down would mean yielding to the demands, but to submit to the United States publicly would be too shameful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Still, the experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the United States &apos; trade war could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
The fact that a rapid policy decision in Washington or Beijing could set the stage for a crash in the economy in either country is actually far more dangerous than has been recognized so far, said Abigail Grace, an associate fellow focused on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria ready to receive refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria asserts that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and requests assistance in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that has lasted more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the country &apos; s conditions were improving.
The situation on the ground is today more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, he said.
The Government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in an effort to restore normalcy.
All the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave their country because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods were now in place.
UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would welcome help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that had promoted the insurgency.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the American team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, outside Paris, France.
The United States now has six consecutive defeats on European soil since its last win in the Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe regained the crown when the Danish team of Captain Thomas Bjorn won the 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight hard for most of the tournament, hit his tee shot into the water on the par-3 16th hole, conceding defeat to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of only four players to ever post a 5-0-0 record since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth lost 5 and 4 to the lowest-ranked player on the European team, Dane Thorbjorn Olesen.
World number one Dustin Johnson was beaten 2 and 1 by Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spanish veteran Sergio García became the European Ryder Cup player with the most wins in the history of the tournament, with 25.5 points in his career.
I do not usually cry, but today I cannot help it.
