Your 12 players have played a very good game.
We will regroup, I will meet with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Committee, and we will move forward.
I love these 12 boys and I am proud to be their captain.
It is now our turn to hang our heads in shame.
They have surpassed us.
Red tide update: Decreasing concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FFWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, irregular bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles along the shoreline from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles inland from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the Hillsborough County coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the Manatee County coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the Sarasota County and its coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the Charlotte County coast, low to high concentrations were reported on the Lee County coast, and low concentrations were reported on the Collier County coast.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No reports of respiratory irritation in the north-west of Florida during the past week.
